With Java 14+, we have the possibility to use [Records (JEP 395, `openjdk.org`)][jep395]. Without knowing anything of the semantics, I will demonstrate the usage with a generic `record Pair`, but we can of course always find more descriptive names.

We define a generic `Pair` of generic types `T` and `U`:

    record Pair&lt;T, U&gt; (T first, U second) {}

And a dummy-implementation of `ObjectA`:

    class ObjectA {
      private final String name;
    
      public ObjectA(String name) {
        this.name = name;
      }
    
      @Override
      public String toString() {
        return &quot;ObjectA{&quot; +
            &quot;name=&#39;&quot; + name + &#39;\&#39;&#39; +
            &#39;}&#39;;
      }
    }

We can then implement our method like this:

    public static Pair&lt;List&lt;ObjectA&gt;, List&lt;List&lt;String&gt;&gt;&gt; foo() {
      return new Pair&lt;&gt;(
          List.of(new ObjectA(&quot;one&quot;), new ObjectA(&quot;two&quot;)),
          List.of(
              List.of(&quot;three&quot;, &quot;four&quot;),
              List.of(&quot;five&quot;, &quot;six&quot;),
              List.of(&quot;seven&quot;, &quot;eight&quot;)));
    }

And call it like this:

